#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:1
msgid "Scheduling and Streams"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:3
msgid ""
"The previous chapters built up a vocabulary for describing GPU work -- "
"`DeviceOperation`s, `and_then` chains, `zip!` bundles. But a description is "
"not execution. At some point, the recipe has to reach a kitchen. This "
"chapter is about the kitchens: what CUDA streams are, how cuda-oxide's "
"scheduling policies assign work to them, and what happens behind the scenes "
"when a `DeviceOperation` becomes a running `DeviceFuture`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:11
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide -- Streams](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-"
"programming-guide/#streams) for the underlying CUDA stream semantics that "
"scheduling policies build on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:15
msgid "Checkout lanes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:17
msgid ""
"Think of a CUDA stream as a **checkout lane** at a grocery store. Each lane "
"processes customers in order -- whoever is first in line gets served first. "
"But multiple lanes operate independently, so lane 1 can ring up a customer "
"while lane 2 bags a different order. The store gets more throughput because "
"work on different lanes overlaps in time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:23
msgid ""
"A GPU works the same way. A **stream** is an in-order queue of operations. "
"Within a single stream, everything executes sequentially -- kernel A "
"finishes before kernel B starts. But if you put kernel A on stream 0 and "
"kernel B on stream 1, they can overlap on the hardware:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:28
msgid ""
"Stream 0:  ┌─── Kernel A ───┐\n"
"           └────────────────┘\n"
"Stream 1:       ┌─── Kernel B ───┐\n"
"                └────────────────┘\n"
"\n"
"           ◄─── time ────────────────►\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:37
msgid ""
"With one stream, everything is serial. With multiple streams, independent "
"work overlaps and the GPU stays busier. This is the fundamental mechanism "
"for concurrency on the GPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:41
msgid "Why you rarely touch streams directly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:43
msgid ""
"In CUDA C++, the programmer creates streams, decides which stream each "
"operation goes on, and manually inserts events when work on one stream "
"depends on results from another. This is powerful but tedious, and it "
"couples every function to a specific concurrency strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:48
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide inserts a layer of indirection: the **scheduling policy**. "
"Instead of choosing a stream yourself, you hand your `DeviceOperation` to "
"the policy, and it picks the stream for you. This means the same pipeline "
"can run on a single stream (for debugging), a pool of four streams (for "
"throughput), or a custom policy you write yourself -- all without changing "
"the pipeline code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:54
msgid "The `SchedulingPolicy` trait"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:56
msgid ""
"A scheduling policy answers one question: \"given this operation, which "
"stream should it run on?\" The trait has three methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:59
msgid "**`init`** -- called once at startup to create the CUDA streams."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:60
msgid ""
"**`schedule`** -- picks a stream and wraps the operation in a `DeviceFuture` "
"for `.await`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:62
msgid ""
"**`sync`** -- picks a stream, executes the operation, and blocks until it "
"finishes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:65
msgid ""
"The policy is `Sync`, meaning a single instance is shared across all "
"operations on a device. Stream selection must be thread-safe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:68
msgid "`StreamPoolRoundRobin` -- the default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:70
msgid ""
"When you call `init_device_contexts(0, 1)`, cuda-oxide creates a "
"`StreamPoolRoundRobin` with four CUDA streams. Every time an operation is "
"scheduled, an atomic counter advances and the next stream in the pool is "
"selected:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:75
msgid ""
"Operation 1  →  Stream 0  ──► ████████\n"
"Operation 2  →  Stream 1  ──►    ████████         (overlaps 1)\n"
"Operation 3  →  Stream 2  ──►       ████████      (overlaps 1, 2)\n"
"Operation 4  →  Stream 3  ──►          ████████\n"
"Operation 5  →  Stream 0  ──►                ████████  (waits for 1)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:83
msgid ""
"The selection is lock-free -- a single `fetch_add` on an `AtomicUsize`, "
"modulo the pool size. The overhead is negligible compared to the cost of GPU "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:87
msgid ""
"Four streams is a good default. It gives the GPU enough in-flight work to "
"overlap kernel execution with memory transfers, without excessive context- "
"switching overhead. For most workloads, you will never need to think about "
"it -- the policy just works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:92
msgid "When round-robin shines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:94
msgid ""
"**Batched inference:** Each batch is an independent pipeline. Round-robin "
"distributes batches across streams, overlapping compute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:96
msgid ""
"**Mixed compute + transfer:** While one stream runs a kernel, another copies "
"data. The GPU's copy engines and compute units work simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:98
msgid ""
"**Many small kernels:** Overlapping launch overhead reduces the gap between "
"kernels, keeping the GPU busier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:101
msgid "When to reconsider"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:103
msgid ""
"**Dependency-heavy chains:** If you build a single `and_then` chain (like "
"the forward pass in the previous chapter), the chain runs entirely on one "
"stream anyway. Round-robin only matters when you schedule *multiple "
"independent* operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:107
msgid ""
"**Very large kernels:** A single kernel that saturates the GPU gains nothing "
"from multi-stream scheduling. The extra streams sit idle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:110
msgid "`SingleStream` -- one lane, strict order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:113
msgid ""
"`SingleStream` is implemented in the scheduling internals but is **not "
"currently wired into `GlobalSchedulingPolicy`** or exposed through "
"`init_device_contexts`. The default setup always uses "
"`StreamPoolRoundRobin`. This section describes the design intent for a "
"future API surface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:119
msgid ""
"For debugging, or when you need guaranteed ordering across *all* operations, "
"`SingleStream` routes everything to one stream. Every operation sees the "
"results of every previous operation, eliminating any possibility of stream-"
"related concurrency bugs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:124
msgid ""
"Operation 1  →  Stream 0  ──► ████████\n"
"Operation 2  →  Stream 0  ──►          ████████   (waits for 1)\n"
"Operation 3  →  Stream 0  ──►                  ████████\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:131
msgid ""
"If you suspect a concurrency bug in your GPU pipeline, switching to "
"`SingleStream` is the fastest way to check. If the bug disappears, it was a "
"missing dependency between operations on different streams. If it persists, "
"the problem is elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:137
msgid "Setting up the runtime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:139
msgid ""
"Before any async operation can run, you initialize the thread-local device "
"context:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:142
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::device_context::init_device_contexts;\n"
"\n"
"init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:148
msgid ""
"The first argument is the default GPU ordinal; the second is how many "
"devices to manage. Under the hood, this registers a thread-local that lazily "
"creates a `StreamPoolRoundRobin` for each device on first use. The pool "
"holds four streams by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:153
msgid ""
"Call this once at the start of your program, before any `.sync()` or `."
"await`. Calling it twice on the same thread returns an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:156
msgid "What happens when you `.await`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:162
msgid ""
"Left: the DeviceFuture three-state machine. On the first poll, GPU work and "
"a `cuLaunchHostFunc` callback are submitted — then `Poll::Pending` is "
"returned. When the GPU finishes, the callback sets an `AtomicBool` and wakes "
"the task. On the second poll, the result is delivered. Right: comparison of "
"`.sync()` (thread blocked the entire time) vs `.await` (thread runs other "
"tasks while the GPU works)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:170
msgid ""
"Here is the full journey of an operation from construction to completion:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:172
msgid ""
"module.kernel_async(&prepared, ...)  ← build a checked recipe (no GPU work)\n"
"        │\n"
"        ▼\n"
"  AsyncKernelLaunch            ← a DeviceOperation, lazy and stream-"
"agnostic\n"
"        │\n"
"        │  .await\n"
"        ▼\n"
"  IntoFuture::into_future()    ← scheduling policy picks a stream\n"
"        │\n"
"        ▼\n"
"  DeviceFuture                 ← bound to a stream, ready for polling\n"
"        │\n"
"        │  first poll()\n"
"        ▼\n"
"  execute() on stream 2        ← GPU work is submitted\n"
"  cuLaunchHostFunc on stream 2 ← host callback enqueued after the kernel\n"
"  return Poll::Pending\n"
"        │\n"
"        │  ... GPU is working, host thread is free ...\n"
"        │\n"
"        │  callback fires on a CUDA driver thread\n"
"        │  → sets AtomicBool, wakes AtomicWaker\n"
"        │\n"
"        │  second poll()\n"
"        ▼\n"
"  return Poll::Ready(Ok(()))   ← result delivered to the caller\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:201
msgid ""
"The key insight is that between the first `poll()` and the callback, **no "
"host thread is occupied**. The async runtime parks the task and runs other "
"tasks. The GPU notifies the runtime when it is done, via the "
"`cuLaunchHostFunc` callback. This is why `.await` scales better than `."
"sync()` for concurrent workloads -- you can have dozens of in-flight "
"operations without tying up a thread for each one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:208
msgid "Manual stream control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:210
msgid ""
"Most of the time, the scheduling policy handles streams for you. But there "
"are situations where you need direct control -- interop with a CUDA library "
"that expects a specific stream, fine-grained overlapping of compute and "
"transfers, or profiling a single kernel in isolation. cuda-oxide exposes the "
"full stream API for these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:216
msgid "Creating streams"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:218
msgid ""
"let ctx = CudaContext::new(0)?;\n"
"let default = ctx.default_stream();  // the per-context default (null) "
"stream\n"
"let custom  = ctx.new_stream()?;     // a new non-blocking stream\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:224
msgid ""
"The default stream has special synchronization semantics in CUDA (it "
"implicitly serializes with most other streams). Non-blocking streams created "
"by `new_stream()` do not have this constraint, which is why the scheduling "
"policy uses them exclusively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:229
msgid "Fork and join"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:231
msgid ""
"A common pattern is to fork a child stream from a parent, run independent "
"work on the child, and join the results back. `fork` creates a new stream "
"with an implicit dependency on the parent's current position -- the child "
"will not start until all prior work on the parent finishes. `join` does the "
"reverse: the parent waits for the child to finish before proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:237
msgid ""
"let main = ctx.default_stream();\n"
"\n"
"// Upload data on main\n"
"let buf_a = DeviceBuffer::from_host(&main, &data_a)?;\n"
"let buf_b = DeviceBuffer::from_host(&main, &data_b)?;\n"
"\n"
"// Fork: children see the uploads\n"
"let child_1 = main.fork()?;\n"
"let child_2 = main.fork()?;\n"
"\n"
"// SAFETY: cfg matches process's indexing/resources and both buffers' "
"bounds.\n"
"// Run independent work in parallel.\n"
"unsafe {\n"
"    module.process(&child_1, cfg, &mut buf_a)?;\n"
"    module.process(&child_2, cfg, &mut buf_b)?;\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"// Join: main waits for both children\n"
"main.join(&child_1)?;\n"
"main.join(&child_2)?;\n"
"\n"
"// SAFETY: cfg matches combine's indexing/resources and both input bounds.\n"
"unsafe { module.combine(&main, cfg, &buf_a, &buf_b) }?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:263
msgid "The GPU timeline for this looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:265
msgid ""
"main:      ██ upload_a ██ upload_b ██ ──fork──────────────── join ──► ██ "
"combine ██\n"
"                                         |                    ^  ^\n"
"child_1:                                 └─► ██ process_a ██ ─┘  |\n"
"                                         |                       |\n"
"child_2:                                 └─► ██ process_b ██ ────┘\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:273
msgid ""
"Under the hood, `fork` and `join` use CUDA events -- `cuEventRecord` on one "
"stream, `cuStreamWaitEvent` on another. The events are GPU-side "
"synchronization tokens; no host thread blocks during the fork or the join."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:277
msgid "Events for fine-grained ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:279
msgid ""
"When `fork`/`join` is too coarse, you can use events directly to establish "
"ordering between specific points in different streams:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:282
msgid ""
"// Record an event on stream A after the kernel finishes\n"
"let event = stream_a.record_event(None)?;\n"
"\n"
"// Stream B waits for that specific point before proceeding\n"
"stream_b.wait(&event)?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:290
msgid ""
"A CUDA event is not owned by a stream -- it is a standalone synchronization "
"token. `record` stamps it at a specific point on one stream; `wait` inserts "
"a dependency into another stream. The event is the rendezvous point: nothing "
"after the `wait` on stream B runs until the event fires on stream A."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:295
msgid ""
"Events are also the standard way to measure GPU execution time. Note that "
"timing requires events created **without** `CU_EVENT_DISABLE_TIMING` -- pass "
"explicit flags to enable timing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:299
msgid ""
"use cuda_bindings::CUevent_flags_enum::CU_EVENT_DEFAULT;\n"
"\n"
"let start = stream.record_event(Some(CU_EVENT_DEFAULT))?;\n"
"// SAFETY: config and arguments satisfy my_kernel's requirements.\n"
"unsafe { module.my_kernel(&stream, config) }?;\n"
"let end = stream.record_event(Some(CU_EVENT_DEFAULT))?;\n"
"end.synchronize()?;\n"
"println!(\"Kernel took {:.2} ms\", start.elapsed_ms(&end)?);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:310
msgid ""
"This measures actual GPU time, not host-side scheduling overhead. "
"`record_event(None)` creates timing-disabled events by default, which cannot "
"be used with `elapsed_ms`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/scheduling-and-streams.md:313
msgid ""
"For everyday async pipelines, you never need to create streams, events, or "
"fork/join manually. The scheduling policy and `and_then` chains handle "
"ordering automatically. The manual API exists for interop, profiling, and "
"advanced optimization."
msgstr ""

